english:
  title: Stele Inscription for Lee Gong, Lord of Wansan
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: "The Lee clan of Jeonju is a great house. From Silla's noble Akan, whose name was Gwang-hui, descended the Grand Commandant Lee Ipjeon, who begat Gung-hyu, who begat Yeom-sun, who begat Seung-sak, who begat Chung-gyeong, who begat Gyeong-yeong, who begat Chung-min, who begat Hwa, who begat Jin-yu, who begat Gung-jin, who begat the Great General Yong-bu. The Great General begat the Court Attendant Lee Rin, who married the daughter of Minister Moon Geuk-gyeom and begat General Yang-mu. General Yang-mu married the daughter of General Lee Kang-je and begat An-sa, a man of bold spirit with ambitions beyond his province. He once governed Yi Province with benevolent administration. Through marriage ties, he moved to Sam-cheok County in Gangneung Province, for he found the land's character pleasing. Yet a dispute with the county magistrate turned to peril, and one warned him of a plot against his life. He fled with his household to the Mongol territories, who settled him in Nanjing and made him a darughaci of the five-thousand household district.\n\nThis darughaci married the daughter of Lee Kong-suk, chief of the Thousand-Ox Guard, and begat the household chief Yi Hang-ri, who inherited his father's position. When the Great Khan set forth to conquer Japan, the warships of the realm gathered in our eastern seas. Our King Chung-yeol sent great ministers to build mighty vessels and lead chosen generals with elite forces to join the campaign. At that time, the Nanjing household chief also came by imperial command to join the assembly. Meeting with King Chung-yeol again and again, he grew ever more reverent and humble, saying: \"That my ancestor fled to the north was but to escape the jaws of the tiger, not from disloyalty to lord and father. I beseech you to forgive his transgression.\" The King replied: \"You are of official lineage—how could you forget your roots? Your bearing shows where your heart truly dwells.\" \n\nThe household chief married the daughter of Choi Ki-yeol, district chief of Deng Province, and begat Chun, elevated to Rank of Commendator. Coming before the throne in succession to his father's loyalty, he received from King Chung-suk even greater honors—a reward for his fidelity. Chun married the daughter of Minister Park Gwang, and both became the father and mother of our Lord Lee.\n\nOur Lord's given name was Ja-chun, and he bore that name as his courtesy title as well. From childhood, he showed uncommon gifts, and as he grew, he excelled in horsemanship and archery, inheriting his father's station. The soldiers delighted to follow him. In the autumn of Myeong-gang's reign, he presented himself before the Late King, who said: \"Your grandfather and father, though their bodies dwelt beyond our realm, kept their hearts loyal to our house. My ancestors cherished them well. See that you bring no shame upon them, and I shall perfect your destiny.\"\n\nDouble-Castle lay remote at the frontier, its governance lax, its lands fertile and its people multiplying. From our eastern and southern provinces, those without fixed holdings came in great numbers. When the court informed the Yuan's Central Secretariat, imperial officials came to investigate, as did inspectors from the Liaodong branch. The Late King dispatched Zhongshu official Li Shou-shan to oversee the joint verification of the registers. The three provinces compared the rolls of old and new households in what was called the \"triple verification count.\" Yet after this, the resettlement faltered, and the people began to drift away. Thus the King entrusted our Lord with this charge, rewarding the loyalty of generations. And so the people found stability in their occupations down to this very day.\n\nIn spring of the year Bing-shen, the Lord came to court. The Late King received him with the words: \"How wearisome it must be to pacify and settle such unruly folk.\" At that time, one brought word that the Qi family plotted rebellion, with officials in Double-Castle implicated. The Late King spoke to the Lord: \"Return to your post and guard our people. Should disturbance arise, act according to my command.\"\n\nIn the fifth month, the rebellion was quelled. The King sent his minister Liu Ren-yu to pursue the remnants and calm the common folk. Yet Liu, upon reaching the frontier, hesitated and dared not advance. The King bestowed upon the Lord the rank of Junior Grand Secretary with the title of Minister of State Affairs. Through General Jeong Sin-gye, he sent secret orders for the Lord to support the assault. The Lord, hearing this command, placed a silencing stick in his mouth and marched at once, joining forces with Liu. Together they pursued Small-Life Leader Gyeong, who abandoned his wife and children and fled into the night.\n\nThen the King issued this proclamation: \"Let those who fled go. The rest remain our people. Neither slay nor abuse them.\" The people rejoiced and came forth with food to welcome our forces. The names of the districts were all restored to their ancient forms: Gao Province, Yao-de, Chang-ping, Yuan-xing, Jeong Province, and Ham Province.\n\nIn the ninth month, the Lord's rank was elevated to Grand Commandant, and he was transferred to Minister of Carriages. He was given an estate in Gaegyeong where he settled. The following autumn, he rose to General of the Thousand-Ox Guard and received additional titles. In that year, I myself became a Remonstrance Official, and seeing the Lord in court, I observed his face ruddy as cinnabar and his beard fine and full. I dared not presume to speak with him directly, yet his countenance remains vivid in my memory even now, unforgotten.\n\nIn the spring of the year Gyeong-ja, the third month, he was appointed Grand Commandant and Judge of the Imperial Manufactories, then sent out as Prefect of Sak-bang Province and Commander of the Military Forces. On the eighteenth day of the fourth month, he fell ill and departed this life. He was forty-six years old. What a loss! When word of his death reached the throne, the King mourned deeply, sending an envoy to weep at his tomb and presenting gifts in accordance with proper rites. The officials all exclaimed: \"The Northeast has lost its pillar!\" In the eighth month of that year, he was buried on the eastern slope of Gwi Province in Ham Province.\n\nThe Lord took three wives. The first, of the Lee clan, bore a son named Won-gye, now a Commandant of Wansan, honored with titles of merit. His second wife, the Lady Choi, was made a Grand Lady of the Three Hans, the daughter of Minister Park Han-gi. She bore a son named Seong-gye, who has become the Judge of the Three Ministries, a Grand Commandant of Wansan, honored with supreme titles of achievement. A third wife, the Lady Kim, bore a son named Ho, now a Commissioner and General. Their daughter married General Jo In-byeok, now Lord of Yong-won, and is honored as the Lady of Jinhwa. The Lord's line is prolific and flourishing across all ranks and stations.\n\nI, Lee Saek, in the year Gye-myo served as a密직提學, lacking in talent though I was. The following year, the Lord came to serve as Vice Commander, and in the year Sin-hae, when he took his place as Judge of the Three Ministries, I was transferred to the position of Minister. The King asked his courtiers: \"How strange that the civilian official Lee Saek and the military commander Seong-gye entered office on the same day—what do the ministers make of this?\" He spoke thus in self-approbation. Yet in the decades since, few of my contemporaries remain, while the Lord and I have maintained a friendship clear and simple as water, steady as an ancient tree. People have sometimes admired our constancy, and I could not but regard his father as my own. Thus I do not hesitate to inscribe this monument to his spirit-way.\n\nThe inscription reads:\n\nI have traced the Lee genealogy back to Silla's great Akan,\nA man of keen intellect who aided his sovereign's rule.\nGeneration upon generation his descendants held high office,\nRiding in state across the northern plains,\nWhere benevolence and might were both displayed.\nLoving the land's character, they made their dwelling there,\nAnd Sam-cheok became to them a second home.\nWhen the magistrate's resentment rose,\nThey severed ties and fled to the Mongol realm.\nThere they received the mandate of ten thousand households,\nAnd virtue passed to generations yet unborn,\nWhile sons served the old throne with gentle reverence,\nTheir embassies ever humble and sincere.\nReturning to their roots, returning to their source,\nThey awakened the age and left their mark of merit.\nAnd our Lord the Minister—\nHow the King praised his loyalty!\nYet Heaven swiftly claimed him,\nAnd who now tends the people's fate?\nHis son, the Judge of the Three Ministries, remains,\nHis name and deeds supreme in his generation,\nHis descendants all honored and eminent.\nThe way of Heaven is not without knowledge.\nWhen roots run deep, the branches flourish,\nWhen the source flows far, the stream runs long.\nThis inscription, crude though it be,\nShall cast its light a thousand years hence."
